The Nigerian Export and Import Bank (NEXIM) has sought the support of the Nigerian Navy to connect Nigeria with the Economic Community of West African States trade corridor. The Managing Director of NEXIM Alhaji Abba Bello said the bank has over the years noticed gaps in linking Nigerian trade to global market such as transportation infrastructure and intra model transportation system. He said the gaps informed the Sealink initiative which culminated into the signing of a Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) with the Nigerian Navy to open inland waters to enhance economic trade and movement of goods and services within the nation and across the globe. The Chief of Naval Staff Vice Admiral Ibok-Ete Ibas said the signing of MoU follows the Nigerian Navy’s attainment of Hydrographic survey and charting capacity with the unveiling of first and second indigenous navigational charts. “Since it is the constitutional responsibility of the Nigerian Navy to coordinate all hydrographic surveys and produce charts for mariners within the Nigerian waters, it was only natural for the Nigerian Navy to be part of this strategic partnership, “ he said. Admiral Ibas said the MoU will guide engagement between the NN and NEXIM Bank towards actualising the overall objectives of the regional sealink project. Bello stated earlier that due to lack of sea trading activities, Nigerian waters became unnavigable hence the need for the partnership for survey and chart.